00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:03.380 align:middle line:10%
>>THERESA BULLARD: We've learned
that string theory provides

00:32:03.380 --> 00:32:06.870 align:middle line:10%
some exciting and beautiful
possibilities for discovering

00:32:06.870 --> 00:32:09.090 align:middle line:10%
a unified theory of everything.

00:32:09.090 --> 00:32:11.940 align:middle line:10%
And string theory is
what has opened the door

00:32:11.940 --> 00:32:14.580 align:middle line:10%
to the multiverse
idea in science.

00:32:14.580 --> 00:32:16.050 align:middle line:10%
How did it do that?

00:32:16.050 --> 00:32:18.600 align:middle line:10%
Well, it goes back to the
issue that string theorists are

00:32:18.600 --> 00:32:23.520 align:middle line:10%
grappling with, the challenge of
identifying the exact geometry

00:32:23.520 --> 00:32:26.070 align:middle line:10%
of the super strings
and extra dimensions

00:32:26.070 --> 00:32:28.080 align:middle line:10%
hidden within our universe.

00:32:28.080 --> 00:32:31.170 align:middle line:10%
They have many candidate
shapes allowed by the math.

00:32:31.170 --> 00:32:34.030 align:middle line:10%
Over 10 to the power
500 possibilities,

00:32:34.030 --> 00:32:36.120 align:middle line:10%
which is a massive number.

00:32:36.120 --> 00:32:38.820 align:middle line:10%
Each geometry
theoretically corresponding

00:32:38.820 --> 00:32:41.910 align:middle line:10%
to its own universe
with a different set

00:32:41.910 --> 00:32:44.160 align:middle line:10%
of physical laws and tuning.

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:47.430 align:middle line:10%
But rather than saying there
can be only one right answer,

00:32:47.430 --> 00:32:50.490 align:middle line:10%
resulting in only one
universe, namely ours,

00:32:50.490 --> 00:32:53.190 align:middle line:10%
string theorists
have instead proposed

00:32:53.190 --> 00:32:57.210 align:middle line:10%
that all of these possibilities
are equally probable

00:32:57.210 --> 00:33:01.020 align:middle line:10%
and likely exist somewhere
within a multiverse.

00:33:01.020 --> 00:33:05.130 align:middle line:10%
Meaning there are at least 10 to
the power 500 differently tuned

00:33:05.130 --> 00:33:09.420 align:middle line:10%
universes out there in
the multiverse, maybe even

00:33:09.420 --> 00:33:11.250 align:middle line:10%
infinite numbers.

00:33:11.250 --> 00:33:15.570 align:middle line:10%
But this part where they say
they're all equally probable

00:33:15.570 --> 00:33:19.710 align:middle line:10%
and all exist, this is the
part where some scientists then

00:33:19.710 --> 00:33:21.390 align:middle line:10%
claim that this
means that there is

00:33:21.390 --> 00:33:25.290 align:middle line:10%
nothing special about the
fine tuning of our universe.

00:33:25.290 --> 00:33:28.260 align:middle line:10%
We simply find these sets of
parameters in our universe

00:33:28.260 --> 00:33:31.080 align:middle line:10%
because we can only
exist in a universe that

00:33:31.080 --> 00:33:33.000 align:middle line:10%
is fine tuned for life.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:36.480 align:middle line:10%
But there are many other types
of universes in the multiverse.

00:33:36.480 --> 00:33:39.640 align:middle line:10%
We are just one possibility
in an infinite sea, nothing

00:33:39.640 --> 00:33:40.440 align:middle line:10%
special.

00:33:40.440 --> 00:33:43.080 align:middle line:10%
Therefore, mystery solved.

00:33:43.080 --> 00:33:44.460 align:middle line:10%
Or not.

00:33:44.460 --> 00:33:47.130 align:middle line:10%
Really, all of this
is speculation based

00:33:47.130 --> 00:33:49.320 align:middle line:10%
on assumptions, not evidence.

00:33:49.320 --> 00:33:51.120 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You agree
with that, Simeon?

00:33:51.120 --> 00:33:52.037 align:middle line:90%
>>HEIN: Yeah, overall.

00:33:52.037 --> 00:33:53.010 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What she says?

00:33:53.010 --> 00:33:56.760 align:middle line:10%
>>HEIN: The science suggests,
at least just coming from it

00:33:56.760 --> 00:33:58.500 align:middle line:10%
mathematically, like
string theory does,

00:33:58.500 --> 00:34:00.990 align:middle line:10%
that there are lots
of parallel realities.

00:34:00.990 --> 00:34:04.830 align:middle line:84%
And whether you get from string
theory or from cosmology,

00:34:04.830 --> 00:34:06.538 align:middle line:84%
they all point in this
direction of there

00:34:06.538 --> 00:34:07.580 align:middle line:90%
being parallel realities.

00:34:07.580 --> 00:34:09.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: There's so much
we haven't discovered yet,

00:34:09.730 --> 00:34:10.770 align:middle line:90%
isn't there?

00:34:10.770 --> 00:34:11.100 align:middle line:90%
>>HEIN: Yeah.

00:34:11.100 --> 00:34:13.380 align:middle line:84%
And if you look at, there is
so much we haven't uncovered.

00:34:13.380 --> 00:34:15.297 align:middle line:84%
If you look at the history
of where we've been

00:34:15.297 --> 00:34:17.010 align:middle line:84%
and where we are
now, we've always

00:34:17.010 --> 00:34:20.730 align:middle line:84%
found the idea of a larger
universe a little bit

00:34:20.730 --> 00:34:23.040 align:middle line:90%
frightening, hard to believe.

00:34:23.040 --> 00:34:25.110 align:middle line:84%
People dealt with
this 500 years ago.

00:34:25.110 --> 00:34:29.400 align:middle line:84%
You think of Copernicus,
Galileo just even suggesting

00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:31.373 align:middle line:84%
that the Earth wasn't
the center, right,

00:34:31.373 --> 00:34:32.790 align:middle line:84%
as your guest is
pointing out here

00:34:32.790 --> 00:34:34.260 align:middle line:90%
that maybe we're not special.

00:34:34.260 --> 00:34:35.580 align:middle line:90%
That was like heresy back then.

00:34:35.580 --> 00:34:36.960 align:middle line:90%
People were burned at the stake.

00:34:36.960 --> 00:34:40.920 align:middle line:10%
And now every day they
discover new exoplanets, right?

00:34:40.920 --> 00:34:43.199 align:middle line:84%
So would it really
be surprising we're

00:34:43.199 --> 00:34:46.590 align:middle line:84%
finding our universe
is infinitely large,

00:34:46.590 --> 00:34:48.210 align:middle line:90%
there's also other universes?

00:34:48.210 --> 00:34:51.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Will technology help
us find these other universes?

00:34:51.870 --> 00:34:52.872 align:middle line:90%
>>HEIN: I think it will.

00:34:52.872 --> 00:34:54.330 align:middle line:84%
These particle
experiments that are

00:34:54.330 --> 00:34:57.270 align:middle line:84%
being done right now that we
talked about a second ago,

00:34:57.270 --> 00:34:59.725 align:middle line:84%
you could find evidence
from particle physics.

00:34:59.725 --> 00:35:01.350 align:middle line:84%
Something, that
something doesn't quite

00:35:01.350 --> 00:35:05.220 align:middle line:84%
fit from our conventional
model of physics,

00:35:05.220 --> 00:35:06.690 align:middle line:84%
and that the only
way to explain it

00:35:06.690 --> 00:35:08.940 align:middle line:84%
would be that there's
some other reality

00:35:08.940 --> 00:35:11.590 align:middle line:84%
that we can't see that's sort
of interacting with our own.

00:35:11.590 --> 00:35:13.470 align:middle line:10%
In fact, physicists
right now are

00:35:13.470 --> 00:35:16.080 align:middle line:10%
proposing something called, the
Many Interacting Worlds model.

00:35:16.080 --> 00:35:20.370 align:middle line:84%
Howard Wiseman from Australia,
serious mainstream physicists

00:35:20.370 --> 00:35:22.770 align:middle line:84%
have said, you know, you
can take quantum mechanics,

00:35:22.770 --> 00:35:25.050 align:middle line:84%
flip it around and look
at quantum mechanics

00:35:25.050 --> 00:35:27.430 align:middle line:84%
as an effect of
multiverses interacting.

00:35:27.430 --> 00:35:28.460 align:middle line:90%
How about that?

00:35:28.460 --> 00:35:29.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:35:29.260 --> 00:35:31.980 align:middle line:84%
>>HEIN: That's it's a huge
number, near infinite number of

00:35:31.980 --> 00:35:32.580 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's dramatic.

00:35:32.580 --> 00:35:34.122 align:middle line:84%
>>HEIN: Multi, they
interact slightly

00:35:34.122 --> 00:35:36.460 align:middle line:84%
with us, which creates what
we call quantum mechanics.

00:35:36.460 --> 00:35:38.640 align:middle line:84%
So physicists are
really starting

00:35:38.640 --> 00:35:40.000 align:middle line:90%
to look at this flip it around.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:41.768 align:middle line:84%
And so you could end
up at multiverses

00:35:41.768 --> 00:35:42.810 align:middle line:90%
from many different ways.

00:35:42.810 --> 00:35:44.143 align:middle line:90%
And it wouldn't seem so strange.

00:35:44.143 --> 00:35:47.078 align:middle line:84%
I mean, again, 500 years ago
we would have really thought

00:35:47.078 --> 00:35:49.370 align:middle line:84%
that it was weird that we
weren't the center, you know.

00:35:49.370 --> 00:35:50.912 align:middle line:84%
That it's a couple
of planets and us.

00:35:50.912 --> 00:35:52.410 align:middle line:90%
And now how big is it?

00:35:52.410 --> 00:35:54.990 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What is antimatter?

00:35:54.990 --> 00:35:58.890 align:middle line:84%
>>HEIN: Antimatter is
something that Paul Dirac,

00:35:58.890 --> 00:36:02.070 align:middle line:84%
the British physicist,
proposed back in 1927.

00:36:02.070 --> 00:36:03.300 align:middle line:90%
And he couldn't believe it.

00:36:03.300 --> 00:36:04.350 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: '27?

00:36:04.350 --> 00:36:05.623 align:middle line:90%
>>HEIN: '27.

00:36:05.623 --> 00:36:06.540 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He was right.

00:36:06.540 --> 00:36:09.207 align:middle line:84%
>>HEIN: He was going through the
equations of quantum mechanics,

00:36:09.207 --> 00:36:14.040 align:middle line:84%
