parallel set of explanations

00:36:14.040 --> 00:36:17.310 align:middle line:84%
that suggested particles
that we hadn't detected yet,

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:20.520 align:middle line:90%
that fit Einstein's equations.

00:36:20.520 --> 00:36:23.178 align:middle line:10%
And he called it, I don't know
if he called it antimatter back

00:36:23.178 --> 00:36:25.470 align:middle line:10%
then, but he suggested that
there were other particles.

00:36:25.470 --> 00:36:27.750 align:middle line:10%
And it took three years
to work the math out.

00:36:27.750 --> 00:36:30.265 align:middle line:84%
And then someone named
Carl Anderson actually

00:36:30.265 --> 00:36:32.640 align:middle line:84%
detected one of these particles
like we're talking about,

00:36:32.640 --> 00:36:35.640 align:middle line:90%
science comes along, in 1932.

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:39.380 align:middle line:84%
They were looking at
particle, particle tracks.

00:36:39.380 --> 00:36:40.530 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: 88 years ago.

00:36:40.530 --> 00:36:41.330 align:middle line:90%
>>HEIN: Yeah.

00:36:41.330 --> 00:36:42.280 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: 88 years ago!

00:36:42.280 --> 00:36:43.080 align:middle line:90%
>>HEIN: 88 years.

00:36:43.080 --> 00:36:47.452 align:middle line:84%
And they realized that the math
had suggested ant-particles.

00:36:47.452 --> 00:36:48.660 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Something was there.

00:36:48.660 --> 00:36:49.170 align:middle line:90%
>>HEIN: They were.

